09680-0}}. {{OCLC|470870988}}.\n:Staten, Clifford L. (2010). ''[https://www.questia.com/read/123839235/the-history-of-nicaragua The History of Nicaragua]'' Greenwood histories of the modern nations. Santa Barbara, California, US and Oxford, UK: Greenwood Press. {{ISBN|978-0-313-36037-4}}. {{OCLC|855554817}}. {{via|[[Questia]]}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}\n:Adams, Richard N. (October 1989). \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/1007079  The Conquest Tradition of Mesoamerica]\". ''The Americas''. Cambridge University Press. '''46''' (2): 119\u2013136. {{DOI|10.2307/1007079}}. {{JSTOR|1007079}}. {{via|[[JSTOR]]}}.\n:Higgins, Bryan (1994). \"Nicaragua\". In Gerald Michael Greenfield, ed., ''[https://www.questia.com/read/23320492/latin-american-urbanization-historical-profiles-of Latin American Urbanization: Historical Profiles of Major Cities]''. Westport, Connecticut, US: Greenwood Press. {{subscription required|via=[[Questia]]}}\n:Lovell, W. George; and Christopher H. Lutz (1992) \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/25765745 The Historical Demography of Colonial Central America]\". Yearbook (Conference of Latin Americanist Geographers) Vol. 17/18, BENCHMARK 1990 (1991/1992): pp. 127\u2013138. Austin, Texas, US: University of Texas Press. {{JSTOR|25765745}}. {{via|[[JSTOR]]}}.\n:Merril, Tim (1993b). \"[http://countrystudies.us/nicaragua/5.htm Colonial Period, 1522\u20131820: The Spanish Conquest]\" in ''[http://countrystudies.us/nicaragua/ Nicaragua: A Country Study]''. Washington, D. C., US: GPO for the Library of Congress. Accessed on 2017-07-07.\n:Pineda, Baron L. (2006) \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctt5hj296.4 Nicaragua\u2019s Two Coasts]\" in ''[https://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctt5hj296 Shipwrecked Identities: Navigating Race on Nicaragua's Mosquito Coast]''. New Brunswick, New Jersey, US: Rutgers University Press. pp. 21\u201366. {{ISBN|978-0-8135-3813-6}}. {{JSTOR|j.ctt5hj296.4}}. {{via|[[JSTOR]]}}.\n:S\u00e1nchez, Consuelo (July 1989). \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/40977379  El r\u00e9gimen colonial espa\u00f1ol en nicaragua]\". ''Bolet\u00edn de Antropolog\u00eda Americana''. '''19''': 131\u2013161. Mexico City, Mexico: Pan American Institute of Geography and History. {{JSTOR|40977379}}. {{via|[[JSTOR]]}}. {{in lang|es}}\n:Velasco, Balbino (1985) \"[https://search.proquest.com/openview/8f13c3049e4b70f19bdbe8827d710816/1 El conquistador de Nicaragua y Per\u00fa Gabriel de Rojas y su testimonio (1548)]\". ''Revista de Indias''. '''XLV''' (176): 373\u2013403. Madrid, Spain: Instituto de Historia, Centro de Ciencias Humanas y Sociales (CSIC). ISSN 0034-8341. {{subscription required}} {{in lang|es}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Nicaragua topics}}\n{{Spanish colonization of the Americas|footer=yes}}\n{{Spanish Empire}}\n\n[[Category:Military history of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Colonial Central America]]\n[[Category:Spanish conquests in the Americas|Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:16th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Spain]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:History of Mesoamerica]]\n[[Category:Spanish conquest of Central America]]\n[[Category:Native American genocide|C]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Pagans]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLa Mosquitia(link changed toLa Mosquitia (Nicaragua)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_conquest_of_Nicaragua"}
{"title_page": "Tony Radakin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Tony Radakin\n|image= Tony Radakin.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Rear Admiral Radakin in 2015\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1965|11|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Oldham]], Lancashire\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1990\u2013present\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)| Admiral]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[First Sea Lord]]<br/>[[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces|Maritime Forces]]<br/>[[HMNB Portsmouth]]<br/>[[Combined Task Force Iraqi Maritime]]<br/>{{HMS|Norfolk|F230|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Blazer|P279|6}}\n|battles= [[Iraq War]]\n|awards= [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (United States)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Antony David Radakin''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CB|ADC}} (born 10 November 1965), is a senior [[Royal Navy]] officer. He has served as [[First Sea Lord]], the professional head of the [[Her Majesty's Naval Service|Naval Service]], since June 2019. He was Chief of Staff, [[Joint Forces Command]], from 2016 to 2018, and the [[Second Sea Lord]] and [[Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]] from 2018 to 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\nRadakin was born on 10 November 1965 in [[Oldham]], Lancashire, England.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /><ref name=\"GOV 1SL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/tony-radakin |title=Admiral Tony Radakin CB ADC |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 June 2019 |website=gov.uk |publisher=Ministry of Defence |access-date=19 June 2019 |quote=First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff}}</ref> He was educated at St. Brendan's College.<ref name=\"WW 2019\">{{cite web |title=Radakin, Vice Adm. Antony David |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-282403 |website=[[Who's Who 2019]] |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=15 February 2019 |date=1 December 2018}}</ref> He studied law at the [[University of Southampton]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] (LLB) degree in 1989.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /> He qualified as a [[barrister]],<ref name=\"GOV new\">{{cite web |title=New military chiefs appointed |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-military-chiefs-appointed |website=GOV.UK |publisher=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=20 May 2019 |language=en |date=3 December 2018}}</ref> and was [[called to the Bar]] at [[Middle Temple]] in 1996.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /> He later studied [[international relations]] and [[defence studies]] at [[King's College London]], completing a [[Master of Arts]] (MA) degree in 2000.<ref name=\"GOV new\" /><ref>'RADAKIN, Rear Adm. Antony David', [[Who's Who 2016]], A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Naval career==\nRadakin gained his commission in the [[Royal Navy]] on 20 October 1990.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/~/media/royal%20navy%20responsive/documents/profiles/radakin%20tony.pdf|title=Rear Admiral Tony Radakin|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=52353|supp=y|page=18701|date=3 December 1990}}</ref> He was promoted to [[Lieutenant commander (Royal Navy)|lieutenant commander]] in 1 November 1996,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54637|supp=y|page=1|date=31 December 1996}}</ref> and went on to become commanding officer of the [[frigate]] {{HMS|Norfolk|F230|6}} in 2003, commanding officer of the US/UK Iraqi Naval Transition Team in 2006, and commanding officer of the US/UK [[Combined Task Force Iraqi Maritime]] in 2010.<ref name=bio/> For this tour he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] by the [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59554|supp=y|page=18540|date=24 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nPromoted to [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|commodore]] on 30 August 2011,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59898|supp=y|page=16983|date=6 September 2011}}</ref> Radakin became commander of [[HMNB Portsmouth]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/1811|title=Naval base commander seen off in style|date=6 October 2011|publisher=Navy News|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> He was appointed Director of Force Development at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] in November 2012.<ref name=appoints>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Ministry%20of%20Defence%20Senior%20Posts.pdf|title=Ministry of Defence and tri-service senior appointments|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Promoted to [[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)|rear admiral]] on 3 December 2014,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61071|supp=y|page=23726|date=9 December 2014}}</ref> he became [[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces and Rear Admiral Surface Ships]] in December 2014,<ref name=bio/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2014/december/22/141222-fleet-awards|title=Fleet awards|publisher=Royal Navy|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> and Chief of Staff, [[Joint Forces Command]], in March 2016.<ref name=appoints/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourgibraltartv.com/society/11698-may-17-chief-of-staff-joint-forces-command-visits-the-rock|title=Chief Of Staff Joint Forces Command Visits The Rock|date=17 May 2016|publisher=Your Gibraltar TV|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nPromoted to [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|vice admiral]] on 27 March 2018 on appointment as [[Second Sea Lord]] and [[Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62252|supp=y|page=6366|date=10 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Admirals-Current.pdf|title=Admirals|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> Radakin was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[2018 Birthday Honours]] three months later.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62310|supp=y|page=B3|date=9 June 2018}}</ref> He was promoted to [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]] and succeeded Admiral [[Philip Jones (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Philip Jones]] as [[First Sea Lord|First Sea Lord and Chief of the Naval Staff]] in June 2019.<ref name=\"GOV 1SL\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=New First Sea Lord appointment announced |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2018/december/03/181202-1sl |website=www.royalnavy.mod.uk |accessdate=3 December 2018 |language=en |date=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/03/generation-innovators-has-appointed-run-military-shake-up-top/|title=A 'generation of innovators' has been appointed to run the military in a shake-up of the top ranks of the Army, Navy and RAF |publisher=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=3 December 2018 |language=en |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1995, Radakin married Louise. Together they have four sons.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /> Radakin is also president of the Royal Navy Squash Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/tony-radakin|title=Admiral Tony Radakin CB ADC|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Tarrant]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Alex Burton]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jonathan Woodcock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Second Sea Lord|Second Sea Lord and Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nicholas Hine]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Philip Jones (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Philip Jones]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[First Sea Lord]]|years=2019\u2013}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{First Sea Lord}}\n{{UK Chiefs of Staff Committee}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radakin, Tony}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Tony Radakin\n|image= Tony Radakin.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Rear Admiral Radakin in 2015\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1965|11|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Oldham]], Lancashire\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1990\u2013present\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)| Admiral]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[First Sea Lord]]<br/>[[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces|Maritime Forces]]<br/>[[HMNB Portsmouth]]<br/>[[Combined Task Force Iraqi Maritime]]<br/>{{HMS|Norfolk|F230|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Blazer|P279|6}}\n|battles= [[Iraq War]]\n|awards= [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (United States)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Antony David Radakin''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CB|ADC}} (born 10 November 1965) is a senior [[Royal Navy]] officer. He has served as [[First Sea Lord]], the professional head of the [[Her Majesty's Naval Service|Naval Service]], since June 2019. He was Chief of Staff, [[Joint Forces Command]] from 2016 to 2018, and the [[Second Sea Lord]] and [[Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]] from 2018 to 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\nRadakin was born on 10 November 1965 in [[Oldham]], Lancashire, England.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /><ref name=\"GOV 1SL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/tony-radakin |title=Admiral Tony Radakin CB ADC |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 June 2019 |website=gov.uk |publisher=Ministry of Defence |access-date=19 June 2019 |quote=First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff}}</ref> He was educated at St. Brendan's College.<ref name=\"WW 2019\">{{cite web |title=Radakin, Vice Adm. Antony David |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-282403 |website=[[Who's Who 2019]] |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=15 February 2019 |date=1 December 2018}}</ref> He studied law at the [[University of Southampton]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] (LLB) degree in 1989.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /> He qualified as a [[barrister]],<ref name=\"GOV new\">{{cite web |title=New military chiefs appointed |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-military-chiefs-appointed |website=GOV.UK |publisher=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=20 May 2019 |language=en |date=3 December 2018}}</ref> and was [[called to the Bar]] at [[Middle Temple]] in 1996.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /> He later studied [[international relations]] and [[defence studies]] at [[King's College London]], completing a [[Master of Arts]] (MA) degree in 2000.<ref name=\"GOV new\" /><ref>'RADAKIN, Rear Adm. Antony David', [[Who's Who 2016]], A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2016</ref>\n\n==Naval career==\nRadakin gained his commission in the [[Royal Navy]] on 20 October 1990.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/~/media/royal%20navy%20responsive/documents/profiles/radakin%20tony.pdf|title=Rear Admiral Tony Radakin|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=52353|supp=y|page=18701|date=3 December 1990}}</ref> He was promoted to [[Lieutenant commander (Royal Navy)|lieutenant commander]] in 1 November 1996,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54637|supp=y|page=1|date=31 December 1996}}</ref> and went on to become commanding officer of the [[frigate]] {{HMS|Norfolk|F230|6}} in 2003, commanding officer of the US/UK Iraqi Naval Transition Team in 2006, and commanding officer of the US/UK [[Combined Task Force Iraqi Maritime]] in 2010.<ref name=bio/> For this tour he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] by the [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59554|supp=y|page=18540|date=24 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nPromoted to [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|commodore]] on 30 August 2011,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59898|supp=y|page=16983|date=6 September 2011}}</ref> Radakin became commander of [[HMNB Portsmouth]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/1811|title=Naval base commander seen off in style|date=6 October 2011|publisher=Navy News|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> He was appointed Director of Force Development at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] in November 2012.<ref name=appoints>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Ministry%20of%20Defence%20Senior%20Posts.pdf|title=Ministry of Defence and tri-service senior appointments|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Promoted to [[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)|rear admiral]] on 3 December 2014,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61071|supp=y|page=23726|date=9 December 2014}}</ref> he became [[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces and Rear Admiral Surface Ships]] in December 2014,<ref name=bio/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2014/december/22/141222-fleet-awards|title=Fleet awards|publisher=Royal Navy|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> and Chief of Staff, [[Joint Forces Command]] in March 2016.<ref name=appoints/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourgibraltartv.com/society/11698-may-17-chief-of-staff-joint-forces-command-visits-the-rock|title=Chief Of Staff Joint Forces Command Visits The Rock|date=17 May 2016|publisher=Your Gibraltar TV|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nPromoted to [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|vice admiral]] on 27 March 2018 on appointment as [[Second Sea Lord]] and [[Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62252|supp=y|page=6366|date=10 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Admirals-Current.pdf|title=Admirals|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> Radakin was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[2018 Birthday Honours]] three months later.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62310|supp=y|page=B3|date=9 June 2018}}</ref> He was promoted to [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]] and succeeded Admiral [[Philip Jones (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Philip Jones]] as [[First Sea Lord|First Sea Lord and Chief of the Naval Staff]] in June 2019.<ref name=\"GOV 1SL\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=New First Sea Lord appointment announced |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2018/december/03/181202-1sl |website=www.royalnavy.mod.uk |accessdate=3 December 2018 |language=en |date=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/03/generation-innovators-has-appointed-run-military-shake-up-top/|title=A 'generation of innovators' has been appointed to run the military in a shake-up of the top ranks of the Army, Navy and RAF |publisher=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=3 December 2018 |language=en |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1995, Radakin married Louise. Together they have four sons.<ref name=\"WW 2019\" /> Radakin is also president of the Royal Navy Squash Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/tony-radakin|title=Admiral Tony Radakin CB ADC|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Tarrant]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Alex Burton]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jonathan Woodcock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Second Sea Lord|Second Sea Lord and Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nicholas Hine]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Philip Jones (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Philip Jones]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[First Sea Lord]]|years=2019\u2013}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{First Sea Lord}}\n{{UK Chiefs of Staff Committee}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radakin, Tony}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n", "name_user": "HandsomeFella", "label": "safe", "comment": "c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Radakin"}
{"title_page": "List of World Heritage Sites in Central America", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a list of [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]s in Central America.\n<!--{{GeoGroupTemplate}}-->\n\n==Legend==\n:'''Site'''; as per officially inscribed name<ref name=list>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list |title=World Heritage List |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n:'''Location'''; at city, regional, or provincial level and geocoordinates\n:'''Criteria'''; as defined by the World Heritage Committee<ref name=\"criteria\">{{Cite web|title=The Criteria for Selection |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/criteria |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n:'''Area'''; in [[hectare]]s and [[acre]]s. If available, the size of the buffer zone has been noted as well. A value of zero implies that no data has been published by UNESCO\n:'''Year'''; during which the site was inscribed to the World Heritage List\n:'''Description'''; brief information about the site, including reasons for qualifying as an endangered site, if applicable\n\n==World Heritage Sites==\n{{Legend|#FFE6BD|\u2020 In danger|outline=silver}}\n{{Legend|#D0E7FF|* Trans-border site|outline=silver}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" \n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| Site\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" | Image \n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | [[World Heritage Site#Selection criteria|Criteria]]\n! scope=\"col\"| Area<br />ha (acre)\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Description\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Refs\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Antigua Guatemala]]\n| [[File:Calle del Arco, Antigua Guatemala.jpg|150x150px|Calle del Arco in Antigua|alt=Street with colorful single-storied houses with window grills.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Guatemala</span>[[Sacatep\u00e9quez Department]],<br />{{flag|Guatemala}}<br/><small>{{coord|14|34|N|90|40|W|type:landmark|name=Antigua Guatemala}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(ii), (iii), (iv)\n| align=\"center\" | {{convert|49|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1979\n| Founded in the early 16th century, Antigua was the capital of the [[Kingdom of Guatemala]] and its cultural, economic, religious, political and educational centre until a devastating earthquake in 1773. Its principal monuments have been preserved largely as ruins and are an excellent example of Spanish colonial architecture.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/65|title=Antigua Guatemala|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Quirigua|[[Archaeological Park and Ruins of Quirigua]]}}\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:GT Quirigua StelaE.JPG|150x150px|Quirigu\u00e1 Stele|alt=Tall stone stele decorated with relief.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Guatemala</span>[[Izabal Department]],<br />{{flag|Guatemala}}<br/><small>{{coord|15|16|14|N|89|2|25|W|type:landmark|name=Archaeological Park and Ruins of Quirigua}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(i), (ii), (iv)\n| align=\"center\" | {{ntsh|0}}&mdash;\n| align=\"center\" |1981\n| Quirigu\u00e1 is an ancient [[Maya civilization|Maya]] archaeological site that flourished during the [[Late Classic]]. The ruins of the site contain outstanding carved stelae and sculpted calendars.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/149|title=Archaeological Park and Ruins of Quirigua|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Panam\u00e1 Viejo|Archaeological Site of [[Panam\u00e1 Viejo]] and [[Casco Viejo, Panama|Historic District of Panam\u00e1]]}}\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Torre de panama viejo.jpg|150x150px|alt=Ruins of a four-storied stone tower.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Panama</span>[[Panam\u00e1 District]], [[Panam\u00e1 Province]],<br />{{flag|Panama}}<br/><small>{{coord|9|00|24|N|79|29|06|W|type:landmark|name=Archaeological Site of Panam\u00e1 Viejo and Historic District of Panam\u00e1}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(ii), (iv), (vi)\n| {{convert|57|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1997<br/><ref group=\"nb\">Extended in 2003 to include the archaeological site of Panam\u00e1 Viejo and name change from ''Historic District of Panam\u00e1, with the Sal\u00f3n Bolivar, Panama'' to the present name.</ref>\n| Founded in 1519, Panam\u00e1 Viejo was the first European settlement on the Pacific coast of the Americas. The Historic District is a 17th-century replacement of the original town and preserves its street plan, architecture and blend of Spanish, French and early American styles.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/790|title=Archaeological Site of Panam\u00e1 Viejo and Historic District of Panam\u00e1|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><br/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/735|title=Decision - 27COM 8C.40 \u2013 Archaeological Site of Panam\u00e1 Viejo and Historic District of Panam\u00e1 (Panama)|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=13 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Guanacaste|[[Area de Conservaci\u00f3n Guanacaste]]}}\n| [[File:Guanacaste National Park.jpg|150x150px|alt=Mountain, grassland and some trees.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Costa Rica</span>[[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]] and [[Alajuela Province|Alajuela]] Provinces,<br />{{flag|Costa Rica}}<br/><small>{{coord|10|51|N|85|37|W|type:landmark|name=Area de Conservaci\u00f3n Guanacaste}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(ix), (x)\n| {{convert|147000|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1999<br/><ref group=\"nb\">Extended in 2004 to include the sector Santa Elena.</ref>\n| Stretching from the Pacific across the [[Cordillera de Guanacaste]] to the Atlantic, the site contains a range of habitats, including some of the most pristine wetland forests worldwide and the best dry forest habitats in Central America; that provide space for several threatened plant and animal species such as the [[saltwater crocodile]], [[leatherback sea turtle]], [[jaguar]], [[jabiru]], [[mahogany]] or [[lignum vitae|guayac\u00e1n]].\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/928|title=Area de Conservaci\u00f3n Guanacaste|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Belize Barrier Reef Reserve System]]\n| [[File:'Brain' coral.JPG|150x150px|alt=Underwater image of a green stone like object with patterns on the surface resembling a brain.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Belize</span>[[Belize District|Belize]], [[Stann Creek District|Stann Creek]] and [[Toledo District]]s,<br />{{flag|Belize}}<br/><small>{{coord|17|19|N|87|32|W|type:landmark_region:BZ|name=Belize Barrier Reef Reserve System}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(vii), (ix), (x)\n| {{convert|96300|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1996 \n| The Belize Barrier Reef Reserve System is the largest reef system on the Northern Hemisphere and harbors several threatened species including [[sea turtle]]s, [[manatee]]s and the [[American crocodile]]. The site has been listed as [[World Heritage in Danger|endangered]] since 2009 due to mangrove cutting and overdevelopment.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/764 |title=Belize Barrier Reef Reserve System |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><br/><ref name=\"33-sess-p81-82\">{{harvnb|33rd session|2009|pp=81\u201382}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Cocos Island]] National Park\n| [[File:Isla del Coco-chatham beach.jpg|150x150px|alt=Hilly coast with grassland, forest and a sandy beach.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Costa Rica</span>[[Puntarenas Province]],<br />{{flag|Costa Rica}}<br/><small>{{coord|5|32|N|87|4|W|type:landmark|name=Cocos Island National Park}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(ix), (x)\n| {{convert|199790|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1997<br/><ref group=\"nb\">Extension of the park's marine zone in 2002.</ref>\n| As the only island in the tropical eastern Pacific, Cocos Island provides unique marine habitats for large [[pelagic fish]] such as sharks, tuna, dolphins or rays.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/820|title=Cocos Island National Park|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><br/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/920|title=Decision - 26COM 23.4 - Cocos Island National Park (Costa Rica)|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Coiba National Park]] and its Special Zone of Marine Protection\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Coiba.JPG|150x150px|alt=Sand beach with palm trees and drift wood.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Panama</span>[[Veraguas Province|Veraguas]] and [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province|Chiriqu\u00ed]] Provinces,<br />{{flag|Panama}}<br/><small>{{coord|7|26|N|81|46|W|type:landmark|name=Coiba National Park and its Special Zone of Marine Protection}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(ix), (x)\n| {{convert|270125|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |2005\n| The park protects islands and marine areas in the [[Gulf of Chiriqu\u00ed]] and is home to an exceptionally large number of endemic mammals, birds and plants as well as to a several threatened species. The marine ecosystem is characterized by a very large biodiversity with 760 species of marine fishes, 33 species of sharks and 20 species of [[cetaceans]]. \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1138|title=Coiba National Park and its Special Zone of Marine Protection|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Darien National Park]]\n| [[File:Tigrillo 2.jpg|150x150px|alt=An ocelot lying on a tree branch.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Panama</span>[[Dari\u00e9n Province]],<br />{{flag|Panama}}<br/><small>{{coord|7|44|N|77|33|W|type:landmark|name=Darien National Park}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(vii), (ix), (x)\n| {{convert|597000|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1981\n| Situated on the border between South and Central America, the park consists of a wide range of habitats including sandy and rocky coastlines, mangroves, swamps, upland and lowland tropical forests. Two Indian tribes, the [[Choc\u00f3 people|Choc\u00f3]] and the [[Kuna people|Kuna]] live in the property.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/159|title=Darien National Park|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background-color: #FFE6BD\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background-color: #FFE6BD\" | [[Fortifications on the Caribbean Side of Panama: Portobelo-San Lorenzo|Fortifications on the Caribbean Side of Panama]]: [[Portobelo, Col\u00f3n|Portobelo]]-[[Fort San Lorenzo|San Lorenzo]]  \u2020 \n| [[File:Portobelo Ruins and bay.jpg|150x150px|alt=Ruins of a fort near water.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Panama</span>[[Col\u00f3n Province]],<br />{{flag|Panama}}<br/><small>{{coord|9|33|14|N|79|39|21|W|type:landmark|name=Fortifications on the Caribbean Side of Panama: Portobelo-San Lorenzo}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(i), (iv)\n| align=\"center\" | {{ntsh|0}}&mdash;\n| align=\"center\" |1980\n| As outstanding examples of Spanish military architecture, the forts were constructed in the 17th and 18th centuries to protect the [[Isthmus of Panama]] which had been of great importance to European colonial trade.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/135|title=Fortifications on the Caribbean Side of Panama: Portobelo-San Lorenzo|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Joya de Cer\u00e9n]] Archaeological Site\n| [[File:ES JoyadeCeren 06 2011 Estructura 9 Area 2 Tamazcal 2106 zoom out.jpg|150x150px|alt=Archaeological excavation of a building.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">El Salvador</span>[[Opico]], [[La Libertad Department (El Salvador)|La Libertad Department]],<br />{{flag|El Salvador}}<br/><small>{{coord|13|49|39|N|89|22|9|W|type:landmark|name=Joya de Cer\u00e9n Archaeological Site}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(iii), (iv)\n| align=\"center\" | {{ntsh|0}}&mdash;\n| align=\"center\" |1993\n| Joya de Cer\u00e9n are the remains of a pre-Hispanic farming community that has been preserved largely intact buried under a volcanic eruption around 590&nbsp;AD. It provides valuable archaeological for everyday life in the 6th century.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/675|title=Joya de Cer\u00e9n Archaeological Site|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Le\u00f3n Cathedral (Nicaragua)|Le\u00f3n Cathedral]]\n| [[File:Kathedrale Leon 2.JPG|150x150px|alt=Main facade of a large church with two massive and low and three main doors.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Nicaragua</span>[[Le\u00f3n (Nicaragua)|Le\u00f3n]]<br />{{flag|Nicaragua}}<br/><small>{{coord|12|26|06|N|86|52|41|W|type:landmark|name=Le\u00f3n Cathedral}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(ii), (iv)\n| {{convert|0.77|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}; buffer zone {{convert|13|ha|abbr=values}}\n| align=\"center\" |2011\n| Built over more than 150 years starting in the mid-18th century, the cathedral's architecture is a fusion of different styles from Baroque to Neoclassicism and an expression of a new Latin American society that developed around the 18th century.\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1236|title=Le\u00f3n Cathedral|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|cop\u00e1n|Maya Site of [[Cop\u00e1n|Copan]]}}\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Copan St H.jpg|150x150px |alt=Stele of human figure with large headdress.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Honduras</span>[[Cop\u00e1n Department]],<br />{{flag|Honduras}}<br/><small>{{coord|14|51|0|N|89|8|0|W|type:landmark|name=Maya Site of Copan}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(iv), (vi)\n| align=\"center\" | {{ntsh|0}}&mdash;\n| align=\"center\" |1980\n| Image is of [[Maya stelae]] H from Cop\u00e1n in Honduras\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/129 |title=Maya Site of Copan|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|diquis|Precolumbian Chiefdom Settlements with [[Stone spheres of Costa Rica|Stone Spheres]] of the Diqu\u00eds}}\n| [[File:Stone sphere.jpg|150x150px|alt=Stone sphere of Costa Rica located at National Museum.]]\n| {{sort|Costa Rica|[[Palmar Sur]], {{flag|Costa Rica}}<br/><small>{{coord|8.911389|N|83.477500|W|name=Precolumbian chiefdom settlements with stone spheres of the Diqu\u00eds}}</small>}} \n| Cultural:<br />(iii)\n| {{convert|6172|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}; buffer zone {{convert|6080|ha|abbr=values}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2014\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1438/|title=Precolumbian Chiefdom Settlements with Stone Spheres of the Diqu\u00eds|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background-color: #FFE6BD\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background-color: #FFE6BD\"| [[R\u00edo Pl\u00e1tano Biosphere Reserve]]<sup>\u2020</sup>\n| [[File:Rio platano.jpg|150x150px|alt=River through dense vegetation. Many tree trunks are lying in the river.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Honduras</span>[[La Mosquitia (Honduras)|La Mosquitia]],<br />{{flag|Honduras}}<br/><small>{{coord|15|44|40|N|84|40|30|W|type:landmark|name=R\u00edo Pl\u00e1tano Biosphere Reserve}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(vii), (viii), (ix), (x)\n| {{convert|500000|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1982 \n| [[World Heritage in Danger|Endangered]] since 2011\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/196|title=R\u00edo Pl\u00e1tano Biosphere Reserve|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|le\u00f3n viejo|Ruins of [[Le\u00f3n Viejo]]}}\n| [[File:Ruinas leon viejo36.jpg|150x150px|alt=Ruins consisting of foundations of small buildings.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Nicaragua</span>Puerto Momotombo, Municipality La Paz Centro, [[Le\u00f3n Department|Department of Le\u00f3n]], <br />{{flag|Nicaragua}}<br/><small>{{coord|12|23|50|N|86|36|37|W|type:landmark|name=Ruins of Le\u00f3n Viejo}}</small>\n| Cultural:<br />(iii), (iv)\n| align=\"center\" | {{ntsh|0}}&mdash;\n| align=\"center\" |2000\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/613|title=Ruins of Le\u00f3n Viejo|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Cordillera de Talamanca|Talamanca Range]]-[[La Amistad International Park|La Amistad Reserves / La Amistad National Park]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Cataract on the Rio Savegre.jpg|150x150px|alt=Narrow waterfall]]\n!style=\"background-color: #D0E7FF\" | <span style=\"display: none;\">Costa Rica</span>[[San Jos\u00e9 Province|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Cartago Province|Cartago]], [[Lim\u00f3n Province|Lim\u00f3n]] and [[Puntarenas Province|Puntarenas]] Provinces, {{flag|Costa Rica}}*; [[Bocas del Toro Province|Bocas del Toro]] and [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province|Chiriqu\u00ed]] Provinces, {{flag|Panama}}*<br/><small>{{coord|9|24|26|N|82|56|20|W|type:landmark|name=Talamanca Range-La Amistad Reserves / La Amistad National Park}}</small>\n| Natural:<br />(vii), (viii), (ix), (x)\n| {{convert|567845|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1983<br/><ref group=\"nb\">Modification of boundaries in 1990 to exclude areas that are not of outstanding universal value and to include the extended [[Chirrip\u00f3 National Park|Chirrip\u00f3]] and Talamanca National Parks.</ref>\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/205|title=Talamanca Range-La Amistad Reserves / La Amistad National Park|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><br/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/3591|title=Decision - 14COM IX - SOC: La Amistad/Talamanca Range (Costa Rica)|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Tikal]] National Park\n| [[File:Tikal-Plaza-And-North-Acropolis.jpg|150x150px|alt=Ruins of stone pyramids and other buildings.]]\n| <span style=\"display: none;\">Guatemala</span>[[Pet\u00e9n Department]],<br />{{flag|Guatemala}}<br/><small>{{coord|17|13|N|89|37|W|type:landmark|name=Tikal National Park}}</small>\n| Mixed:<br />(i), (iii), (iv), (ix), (x)\n| {{convert|57600|ha|abbr=values|sortable=on}}\n| align=\"center\" |1979\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/64|title=Tikal National Park|publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Location of sites==\n\n{{location map+ |Central America |width=800 |float=center |caption=Location of World Heritage Sites in Central America|places=\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=14.566667 |long=-90.733333 |label=[[Antigua Guatemala]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=15.269444 |long=-89.040278 |label=[[Archaeological Park and Ruins of Quirigua|Quirigua]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=9.005556 |long=-79.485833 |label=[[Panam\u00e1 Viejo|Panam\u00e1 Viejo ]]and [[Casco Viejo, Panama|Historic District of Panam\u00e1]]|Panam\u00e1|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=10.85 |long=-85.616667 |label=[[Area de Conservaci\u00f3n Guanacaste|Guanacaste]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=17.315556 |long=-87.534444 |label=[[Belize Barrier Reef]]|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=5.518889 |long=-87.071667 |label=[[Cocos Island]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=7.466667 |long=-81.783333 |label=[[Coiba National Park|Coiba N.P.]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=7.736111|long=-77.547222 |label=[[Darien National Park|Darien N.P.]]|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=9.553889 |long=-79.655833 |label=[[Fortifications on the Caribbean Side of Panama: Portobelo-San Lorenzo|Caribbean Fortifications]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Central America |lat=13.8275 |long=-89.369167 |label=[[Joya de Cer\u00e9n]]|position=bottom}}\n