ess of Honduras]]  (consulted 2012).[https://web.archive.org/web/20140502033354/http://www.honduraseducacional.com/Leyes/LeyGeneraldelAmbiente.pdf]\n* '''General law of the Environment and General Regulation of the Environment''', Office of the Environment, Publisher Guaymuras; Honduras, 1995.\n* Database biodiversity in Honduras Wild Honduras  (consulted 2012).[http://www.hondurassilvestre.com/]\n* Decree No. 104-93 issued by the Sovereign [[National Congress of Honduras]]  (consulted 2012).[https://web.archive.org/web/20140502033354/http://www.honduraseducacional.com/Leyes/LeyGeneraldelAmbiente.pdf]\n* '''General law of the Environment and General Regulation of the Environment''', Office of the Environment, Publisher Guaymuras; Honduras, 1995.\n* Database biodiversity in Honduras Wild Honduras  (consulted 2012).[http://www.hondurassilvestre.com/]\n\n[[Category:Fauna of Honduras| ]]\n[[Category:Flora of Honduras| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=June 2016}}\n{{cleanup rewrite|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n[[File:2006_March_15_jason2.jpg|thumb|200x200px|Sight of a [[Shark]] near of the Island of [[\u00datila]] in Honduras]]\nThe '''flora and fauna of [[Honduras]]''' reflects the country's geographical location inside the [[tropics]]. This has allowed for diverse species of plants and animals to be adapted, but some of them are now in danger of [[extinction]]. This has posed the Honduran government, offices and nature organizations to look after the protection of the local environment, like the creation of [[nature reserve]]s.\n\n== Flora ==\nThe [[flora]] of Honduras is very varied.\nPluvioselva, classified a [[tropical rain forest]], is one of its most impressive vegetal populations. Ecologists designated it \"Hygrophilous Megat\u00e9rmic formation\", for corresponding to regions of high humidity and constant high temperatures, with a single dominant species, like pines or firs, covering big areas. \n\nThe eastern part of the country, ''[[La Mosquitia]]'', has many plants trepadoras or enredaderas, like the lianes and many epifitas, most strikingly the orchids. Adapted to the humid environment, trees are enormous and do not possess deep roots sustaining thanks to the big spurs, while the leaves are large and many. The tree trunks are straight and smooth and their first branches are high above the forest floor. The rainforest corresponds to parts of the northern region below 600 meters in elevation; there is not dry station entirely clear-cut and covers 29% of the total of the surface of the country. Among the more typical vegetal species in this region biogeogr\u00e1fica: Real cedar (Cedrela Mexican), Common [[Cedrus|Cedar]] ([[Cedrela odorata]]), mahogany (Swetonia [[Mahogany|mahogoni]] L.), tree of Mar\u00eda ([[Calophyllum brasiliense]]), Cort\u00e9s (Tabebuia guayacan), \"Espavel\" or Mijao ([[Anacardium excelsum]]), guayabo ([[Psidium|Guayab\u00f3n]]) or (Tarminalia amazonia). \n\nNumerous palm trees exist near the coasts, as well as tropical fruit trees and multicolored [[Flower|flowering plants]]. It is very common to find textile plants like [[cotton]] or pacaya. Also there are many medicinal plants like [[chicory]], [[Dysphania ambrosioides|apazote]] and the [[Tolu balsam|Balsam of Tol\u00fa.]] They use  like producing trees of rubber ([[Ficus elastica]]) and [[resin]], the espino white and the [[Ricinus|palmacristi]] (Ricinus communis)\n\n== Fauna ==\nHonduras fauna is very rich and varied being the most common the ones of arboreal life and those that live in the fluvial currents [[Lacustrine|lacustrine waters.]] Big animals are not very numerous but there are hundreds of reptile species, amphibians and birds; lizards and a lot of varieties of fish in the currents. Cute, bats and myriads of birds abound in the trees. Since there is not cold station, thousands of varieties of [[insect]]s population is wide: wasps, ants, mosquitos, zancudos, [[Phlebotomus|jejenes]] and others. Between the mammals find : \"Danto\" or Tapir ([[Baird's tapir|Tapirus bairdii]]), [[wild boar]] or Pecar\u00ed (Tayassu pecari), Jag\u00fcilla (His americanensis), Tiger or [[jaguar]] (Felis onca), cougar (Felis concolor), Tigrillo (Felis pardalis), [[Colocolo|wildcat]] or Caucel (Felis Wiedii), Yaguarundi or small [[cougar]] (Felis yaguaroundi), [[bat]] (Vampirus spectrum), [[Nasua|pizote]] alone (Nasua narica), [[Procyon (genus)|mapach\u00edn]] (Procyon lotor), Dare anteater (Myrmecophaga tridactyla), etc. Avifauna species are also numerous and very abundant some of them are: colibr\u00edes or sparrows in more than 20 different species; the viudita (Trogon rufus), the [[Woodpecker|bird carpenter]] (Phleoceastes guatemalensis), the lechuza (Pulsatrix perspicillata), the tecolote (Ciccaba virgata), the [[Toucan|Tuc\u00e1n]] or beak of razor (Rhanfastus sulfuratus and Pteroglosus torcuatus), lora yellow nape (Amazon ochrocephala), [[Finsch's parakeet|perico]] green of the coast (Aratinga finschi), king [[Black vulture|zopilote]] or [[Andean condor|condor]] centroamericano (Sarcoramphus pope), [[Wagner's bonneted bat|Eumops glaucinus.]] \n\nBetween the reptiles are the yellow beard (Botrox atrox), tamag\u00e1s (Botrox nasuta), [[Porthidium nasutum]], [[boidae|boa]] (Constrictor imperatur), [[Jingle bell|cascabel]] (Crotalus durissus), green [[Green sea turtle|turtle]] (Chelonia mydas), [[Caiman (genus)|alligator]] coffee (Caiman cocodrylus fuscus), [[lizard]] ( Cocodrylus acutus), [[Coral snake|serpent of choral]], [[West Indian fuzzy chiton|Acanthopleura granulata]], [[Brown basilisk|Basiliscus vittatus.]] Other reptiles are the [[iguana]]s that  mimetizan with the tones varied of the forest; the freshwater turtles like the caguama ([[Loggerhead sea turtle|Caretta caretta]]) and between the amphibians are abundant the toads and the frogs trepadoras of varied species.\n\nThe coasts of Honduras, are  bathed north and east by Caribbean sea and in the south by the Pacific Ocean at [[Gulf of Fonseca]], in turquoise waters of [[Caribbean Sea|Sea Caribbean]] can be appreciated  by means of diving coral [[Coral reef|reefs]] with a big diversity of [[Algae|calcareous seaweeds]], [[Red algae|red seaweeds]], (Rhodophyta), like [[Seagrass|marine meadows]], between other aquatic plants that tackle a natural [[ecosystem]].\n\nLarge species of fauna can be found in Honduran coasts, there can be found [[Whale shark|Shark whales]], [[Oceanic dolphin|dolphins]], and a big variety of tropical fish, [[Caridea|shrimps]] (Caridea) and many more. \n\n===Insects===\nSince there is not a [[Winter|cold season]], thousands of varieties of [[insect]]s grown on Honduras: [[wasp]]s, [[ant]]s, [[mosquito]]s, [[zancudo]]s, [[Phlebotomus|jejenes]] and others.\n\n===Mammals===\nAmong the [[mammal]]s: \n* Tapir ([[Baird's tapir|Tapirus bairdii]]), \n* [[Wild boar]]\n* Pecar\u00ed (''[[Tayassu pecari]]''), \n* Jag\u00fcilla (''[[Sus americanensis]]''), \n* [[Jaguar]] (''Felis onca''), \n* [[Cougar]] (''Felis concolor'')\n* [[Ocelot|Tigrillo]] (''Leopardus pardalis''),\n* [[Colocolo]]\n* Caucel (''[[Felis wiedii]]''), \n* Yaguarundi (''[[jaguarundi|Herpailurus yagouaroundi]]''), \n* [[Spectral bat]] (''Vampyrum spectrum'')\n* [[Wagner's bonneted bat]] (''Eumops glaucinus'')\n* [[Pizote]] Alone (''Nasua narica''), \n* Mapach\u00edn (''[[Procyon lotor]]''), \n* I dare anteater (''[[Myrmecophaga tridactyla]]'')\n\n===Birds===\n[[File:Honduran_Emerald_(Amazilia_luciae)_(2495402213).jpg|thumb|200x200px|Colibr\u00ed Emerald of Honduras or amazilia Honduran]]\nBirds are varied and very abundant, among which: \n* [[Violetear|Colibr\u00edes]] or [[American sparrow|sparrow]]s in more than 20 different species; One of them is the [[Honduran emerald|emerald colibr\u00ed]], an [[endemic species]].\n* The viudita (''[[Trogon rufus]]''), \n* The [[Woodpecker|bird carpenter]] (''[[Campephilus guatemalensis]]''), \n* The lechuza (''[[Pulsatrix perspicillata]]''), \n* The tecolote (''[[Ciccaba virgata]]''), \n* The [[Toucan|Tuc\u00e1n]] or beak of razor (''[[Ramphastos sulfuratus]]'' and ''[[Pteroglossus torquatus]]''), \n* Lora yellow nape (''[[Amazona ochrocephala]]''), \n* [[Finsch's parakeet|perico]] Green of the coast (''[[Aratinga finschi]]''), \n* King [[Black vulture|zopilote]] or [[Andean condor|condor]] centroamericano (''[[Sarcoramphus papa]]'')\n\n===Reptiles===\nThere are 264 species of [[reptile]]s known from Honduras, including 59 species that are [[endemic]] to the country. These include [[crocodilia]]ns (two species, the [[spectacled caiman]] ''Caiman crocodilus'' and the [[American crocodile]] ''Crocodylus acutus''), lizards (103 species), snakes (142 species), and turtles (17 species).<ref name=McCranie2015/>\n\nThe reptiles include the following:\n* Common lancehead ''[[Bothrops atrox]]''\n* Hognosed pitviper ''[[Porthidium nasutum]]''\n* Common northern boa ''[[Boa constrictor imperator]]''\n* South American rattlesnake ''[[Crotalus durissus]]''\n* [[Brown basilisk]] ''Basiliscus vittatus''\n* [[Green sea turtle]] ''Chelonia mydas''\n\n{{see also cat|Reptiles of Honduras}}\n\n===Amphibians===\nThere are 137 species of [[amphibian]]s (frogs, toads, salamanders, and caecilians) known from Honduras, including 52 species that are [[endemic]] to the country. [[Frog|Anurans]] are the most species-rich group (97 species), followed by [[salamander]]s (38 species) and [[caecilian]]s (2 species).<ref name=McCranie2015>{{cite journal |last1=McCranie |first1=James R. |year=2015 |title=A checklist of the amphibians and reptiles of Honduras, with additions, comments on taxonomy, some recent taxonomic decisions, and areas of further studies needed |journal=Zootaxa |volume=3931 |issue=3 |pages=352\u2013386 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3931.3.2|pmid=25781832 }}</ref> While new species are still expected to be discovered, [[chytridiomycosis]] and deforestation are threats to the amphibian fauna.<ref name=McCranie2015/> At least one species, the frog ''[[Craugastor chrysozetetes]]'', is believed to be [[extinct]].<ref>{{cite iucn |author1=Cruz, G.|author2=Wilson, L.D.|author3=McCranie, R.| title = ''Craugastor chrysozetetes'' | volume= 2004 | page = e.T56513A11488131| year = 2004 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2004.RLTS.T56513A11488131.en }}</ref>\n\n{{see also cat|Amphibians of Honduras}}\n\n===Coral===\nThe coasts of Honduras, to the north and east are on the Caribbean and in the south by the [[Gulf of Fonseca]]. In the turquoise waters of the [[Caribbean Sea|Sea Caribbean]] can appreciate by means of diving the [[Coral reef]]s with their diversity of [[Algae|calcareous seaweeds]], [[Red algae|red seaweeds]], (Rhodophyta), like [[Seagrass|marine meadows]], among other aquatic plants that tackle a natural [[ecosystem]].\n\nAmong the fauna that can be found on the Honduran coasts, are the [[Whale shark|Shark whale]], [[Oceanic dolphin|dolphins]],a variety of tropical fish, [[Caridea|shrimp]] (Caridea) and many other species. <div class=\"\" align=\"center\">\n\n==Gallery==\n{| class=\"toc\" style=\"float:center; margin: 0.5em 0.5em 0.5em 1em; padding: 0.5e\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"2\" width=\"800px\"\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#green; color:white; font-size:100%\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"green\" |'''Biodiversity of Honduras'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"white\" valign=\"center\" |[[File:Agaveespinho2.jpg|125x125px]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"white\" valign=\"center\" |[[File:Tillandsia_flabellata0.jpg|125x125px]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"white\" valign=\"center\" |[[File:AnthuriumAndraenum.jpg|125x125px]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"white\" valign=\"center\" |[[File:American_Sweetgum_Liquidambar_styraciflua_Fruit_Context_2500px.jpg|125x125px]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\" align=\"center\" |[[Agave]]\n| style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\" align=\"center\" |[[Tillandsia flabellata]]\n| style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\" align=\"center\" |[[Anthurium]]\n| style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\" align=\"center\"